USING POSTGRESQL

 

The database PostgreSQL uses the following syntax:

 

Select distinct rows by using DISTINCT operator.

  • Filter rows by using WHERE clause.
  • Sort rows by using the ORDER BY clause.
  • Select rows based on various operators such as BETWEEN, IN and LIKE.
  • Group rows into groups by using GROUP BY clause
  • Apply condition for groups by using HAVING clause.
  • Join to another table by using INNER JOIN, LEFT JOIN, RIGHT JOIN clauses.

 

 

PostgreSQL SELECT statement syntax

Let’s start with a basic form of the SELECT statement to query data from a  table. The following illustrates the syntax of the SELECT statement; this is the most simple way to get data from a database in PostgreSQL

SELECT column_1,

       column_2,

       ...

FROM table_name

 

The SELECT statement in more detail:

  • First, you specify a list of columns in the table from which you want to query data in the SELECT clause. You use a comma between each column in case you want to query data from multiple columns. If you want to query data from all column, you can use an asterisk (*) as the shorthand for all columns.
  • Second, you indicate the table name after the FROM keyword

Notice that SQL language is case insensitive. It means if you use SELECT or select the effect is the same. By convention, we will use SQL keywords in uppercase to make the code easier to read and stand out clearly.

Returns data in the form of a results table.

PROS

1. Easy setup

2. Open source, low-cost.

3. ACID compliant. (Atomic, Consistent, Isolated, Durable) For outstanding transactions reliability. This is an industry standard for reliability of databases and makes it suitable for 95 percent of use cases.

4. Supports high concurrent loads. (Multi-Version-Concurrency Control).

5. No costs or licensing problems, or auditing.

6. Extensible, able to be upgraded locally with your own source code, plus an active community of developers who contribute.

7. Available for almost every brand of Unix, and available for Windows using Cygwin framework. Native Windows support is available for version 8 and above.

8. Many GUI options

9. Query optimizer is superior to many.

10. Built-in NoSQL key-value store.

11. Built-in binary JSON storage like Mongo.

12. Cloud hosting

13. Non-relational database support, such as JSON, JSONB, XML, etc. 

14. High support system.

 

CONS

1. Takes a long time to learn. 

2. Slower than MySQL.

3. High learning curve. 

4. Installation and configuration is difficult for beginners. 

5. Not as good as an Object Data Manager.

 

Best suited for almost any scenario, except for possibly speed.

1. How do you store data on ArangoDB?
Key/value pairs, JSON document collections, graphs.

Collections - Documents don't have to use the same schema. <Can documents be used in multiple collections?>
Arango allows for querying across multiple collections of documents. Other NoSQL do not allow for this.

Graph databases - Allows for relationship modelling. You link documents from other collections. This will create a property graph.


Arango does not support SQL. Arango uses AQL. A query is sent to the server. AQL can read and modify data. AQL does not allow for creating and dropping databases, or making indexes. It is used to manipulate the data. It is similar to SQL.

Single servers use a transactional execution. If data modification fails, changes will be rolled back automatically before they happened.

 

2. Pros/Cons
It is not useful for massive data set distribution with thousands of nodes/huge data sets.
Node.js uses a single threaded environment. ArangoDB is multithreaded. Because of this, Node integration can cause problems. You can run Foxx under node.js.


Uses V8 engine. Written in C++.

4. What is the database good for?
It can act as a general purpose db, and allows for documents and graphs. Works well with Web Applications. It is a general purpose database, which allows for flexibility with web applications. It allows transition from a single-server to graph data modelling. This avoids changing technology in the middle of a project.

Foxx is the JavaScript API. Arango uses JSON docs. It is built to be lean by using single page JavaScript applications.

It can use transaction records. Allows for ACID. Arango will accept data changes, then return to the caller once the write is successful. This can cause problems with speed by causing extra system calls. Unlike SQL, the transaction in Arango is server, without the client interaction. 1.) What is the command line?
The command line is a command-line user interface (CLI), also known as a console user interface, and character user interface (CUI). It is a means of interacting with a computer program where the user (or client) issues commands to the program in the form of successive lines of text (command lines). Most casual computer users are accustomed to interacting with computers using a graphical user interface (GUI) which uses icons and menus and is most common. A program which handles the interface is called a command language interpreter or shell. Simply, it is a place where a user types in commands to the computer.

Command line is sometimes preferred by more advanced users because it allows for a more precise and powerful way to control programs and how the computer operates. Once instructed the computer will carry out a task you type in the command prompt if it’s formatted correctly and it understands. Using the command line allows access to the computers full capability, which comes with risks. Instructing the computer to carry out a task can cause damage and unknown results if you are not sure what exactly the command does. Commands must be formatted correctly for the computer to understand what it is you want it to carry out.

Commands have a syntax that must be followed for the computer to properly execute what it is the user wants it to do. The notation of a command has three parts: the utility, the flag, and the arguments. The part that always comes first is the utility and most of the time can be used as a command on its own. They indicate the general idea of what you want carried out. The other parts have different rules and specifically alter the way a command is processed. Flags usually come between the utility and the argument and they alter or modify how the utility operates. They can be thought of as options or preferences for the utility. Flags always start with either one or two dashes. Arguments are used when there is no default setting and the utility needs to know exactly what action you want implemented. They usually come at the end of the command and multiple or zero arguments may be used.

To use the command line you must first must find the program that allows you to execute commands. Depending on the type of operating system your computer is running will determine what program you use. For a Mac OS you will use the Terminal program application to use the command line. Windows operating systems command line program is non-standard and more difficult to use, so it’s best to install a separate command line program. Linux users will use Konsole or Terminal depending on what window manager they are using. Some common commands we will use are: the ls utility, which lists the contents of directories, -l flag indicates the long form or more information of the contents of the directiory, cd changes the current working directory to the directory you specify, pwd prints the working diretory to show where you are, cp copies a file to a location you specify, mv moves a file to a location you specify, rm deletes a file permanently and there is no undo to get it back, git init initilizes your local directory as a Git repoitory, git add adds files to your local repository, git commit -m commits g stages files to your local repository, git remote -v verifies the new remote URL, git push -u origin master pushes the changes in your local repository up to the remote repository you specified as the origin.

 

2.) When I type in `git` or `node` into my terminal, how does it execute?
They execute by using these programs installed on your computer to allow the user to use the command line interface to interact with the programs. They allow the user to run all available functionality of the programs unlike GUI versions.

 

3.) What is a REPL?
REPL is a Read–Eval–Print Loop (REPL), also known as an interactive top level or language shell, is a simple, interactive computer programming environment that takes single user inputs (i.e. single expressions), evaluates them, and returns the result to the user; a program written in a REPL environment is executed piecewise. A REPL environment allows users to access relevant features of an operating system in addition to providing access to programming capabilities.

In npm, there are two ways to install things: locally and globally. Whether to install a package globally or locally depends on the global config, which is aliased to the -g command line switch.

A global install will install modules beyond the scope of the local project and you can use that package (program) in the terminal shell, command line etc. Installing locally only makes the package available to the current project

5. What are flags?

Flags, also known as switches are command-line options that modifies the operation of a command and its effect is determined by the program.  Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by spaces. Flags can be in shorthand form of letters or full words e.g. 'command –g –f –v'  or 'command –global –force --verbose'
